    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Selinum alatum improperly include inducing vomiting, exacerbating asthma, triggering seizures, causing diarrhea, and inducing allergic reactions. These adverse effects can occur due to the plant's toxic compounds, particularly sesquiterpene lactones and essential oils, which can cause gastrointestinal irritation, respiratory distress, and neurological dysfunction. The improper use of Selinum alatum may lead to an imbalance of these compounds, resulting in the aforementioned side effects. In severe cases, the consumption of large quantities of the plant can cause seizures, a potentially life-threatening condition. The individual's susceptibility to these side effects can vary depending on factors such as the plant's preparation, dosage, and individual tolerance.",
    "uses": "Selinum alatum, a plant native to certain regions, has been used in traditional medicine for various purposes. It is believed to possess anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties, which have been utilized to treat wounds and infections. The plant's extracts may also have antiseptic and antifungal effects, making it a potential remedy for skin conditions and fungal infections. Additionally, Selinum alatum has been used to treat digestive issues, such as indigestion and diarrhea, due to its carminative properties. However, more research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of using Selinum alatum for medicinal purposes.",
    "taxonomy": "Selinum alatum is classified as a species of flowering plant in the carrot family (Apiaceae). The genus Selinum belongs to the order Apiales, which is a group of plants that also includes the ash tree family (Oleaceae) and the ginseng family (Araliaceae). Further, it is a member of the subfamily Apioideae, which includes plants like celery and caraway. Selinum alatum is native to Europe and Western Asia. It is also known by its synonym, Selinum silphiatum.",
    "benefits": "Selinum alatum is a plant species known for its various health benefits. Its extracts have been traditionally used to treat digestive issues and alleviate symptoms of indigestion. Additionally, the plant is believed to have anti-inflammatory properties, which can help reduce swelling and pain. Some studies suggest that Selinum alatum may also have antioxidant properties, which can help protect the body against free radicals. Further research is needed to confirm the full extent of its health benefits.",
    "parts": "Selinum alatum, also known as winged carrot or winged celery, is a plant species used in traditional medicine. The entire plant, including its leaves, stems, and roots, has been utilized in various cultures for its medicinal properties. However, more research is needed to fully understand its potential health benefits and the specific parts used for medicinal purposes. The plant is believed to have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which may contribute to its medicinal value. Further studies are required to confirm the specific medicinal parts of Selinum alatum and their uses in traditional medicine.",
    "intro": "Selinum alatum, also known as prickly carrot or winged carrot, is a perennial plant species belonging to the carrot family (Apiaceae). This plant is valued for its potential health benefits, including anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which may help alleviate symptoms of digestive issues, arthritis, and other inflammatory conditions. The bioactive constituents of Selinum alatum include flavonoids, sesquiterpenes, and alkaloids, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In herbal medicine, Selinum alatum is commonly used to make teas, infusions, and tinctures, which are often employed to treat a range of health conditions, including respiratory issues and skin problems."
